Question 1

Some archaeologists theorize that ancient Egyptians interbred with several different immigrant populations over thousands of years. To see if there is any indication of changes in body structure that might have resulted, they measured 30 skulls of male Egyptians dated from 4000 B.C.E. and 30 others dated from 200 B.C.E. We will be using this data to conduct a classic independent t-test to compare the means of the two epochs.

  • Thomson and Randall-Maciver, Ancient Races of the Thebaid, Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1905.

The data can be found in “SkullsPartial.csv”. The column “mb” measures the maximal breadth of the skull.

The data is in the “tidy format”. Find a way to calculate the means for both epochs, as well as the difference between the means. No special packages are required for this. You have already learned methods which can help you here.


There are a bunch of basic ways to do this with tidy formatted data, here are a few simple methods. The second and third methods are the most preferable in this instance because they work even if the data is out of order.

library(tidyverse)
skulls <- read_csv("../Data/SkullsPartial.csv")

# METHOD 1.
# You can index the values you need specifically.  
# Note: if the data is not in a logical order (i.e., if it is shuffled) this method doesn't work.

m_4000 <- mean(skulls$mb[1:30])
m_200 <- mean(skulls$mb[31:60])
m_diff <- m_4000 - m_200
## m_4000 = 131.367
## m_200 = 135.5
## m_diff = -4.133


# METHOD 2.
# You can use the filter function and pull out the column you want as a vector.

m_4000 <- mean(filter(skulls, epoch == "c4000BC")$mb)
m_200 <- mean(filter(skulls, epoch == "c200BC")$mb)
m_diff <- m_4000 - m_200
## m_4000 = 131.367
## m_200 = 135.5
## m_diff = -4.133


# METHOD 3.
# You can use a logical statement inside your index to subset according to the grouping column "epoch".

m_4000 <- mean(skulls$mb[skulls$epoch == "c4000BC"])
m_200 <- mean(skulls$mb[skulls$epoch == "c200BC"])
m_diff <- m_4000 - m_200
## [1] "m_4000 =  131.367"
## [1] "m_200 = 135.5"
## [1] "m_diff = -4.133"

Note: depending on how you subtract the group means, the mean difference will be either negative or positive.

Question 3

Using the skull data, calculate the pooled variance.

# Group Sample Size
n_4000 <- length(skulls$mb[skulls$epoch == "c4000BC"])
n_200 <- length(skulls$mb[skulls$epoch == "c200BC"])

# Pooled Variance

Using the skull data, calculate the pooled standard error.

Question 5

df <- n_4000 + n_200 - 2

Question 6

Test \(H_0: \mu_{_\text{4000}} - \mu_{_\text{200}} = 0\).

Use of t.test() is not permitted.

Make sure to report:

  • the test statistic
  • p-value
  • whether your reject or fail to reject the \(H_0\)
mu <- 0
t <- (m_diff - mu) / se

# Since the test statistic is negative in this case (i.e., below 0), 
  # we calculate the p-value from left to right.
p <- pt(t, df = df) * 2
## Test statistic: -3.507
## p = 0.001
## Since p < .05 we reject the null hypothesis.

Note: depending on how you subtracted the means, the test statistic will be either postive or negative. This will impact the direction you need calculate your p-value.



Question 7

A researcher states their null hypothesis about the skull data as \(H_0: \mu_{_\text{4000}} < \mu_{_\text{200}}\).

Another way of expressing this is by writing: \(H_0: \mu_{_\text{4000}} - \mu_{_\text{200}} < 0\).

Given the null hypothesis being expressed, answer the following questions:


a.

Is this a one or two-tailed hypothesis?

  • One-tailed


b.

How would you interpret this hypothesis in plain English?

  • The breadth of 4000 B.C.E. skulls are smaller (on average) than 200 B.C.E. skulls.


c. 

In which tail is the critical region located for this hypothesis’ test statistic?

  • Right tail.

    • Rationale for those interested: Since the null hypothesis states that the difference between 4000BCE and 200BCE will be anything LESS than 0, you need to find a mean difference greater than 0 to falsify the claim.


d. 

Given what you said in “c.”, which direction should a p-value be calculated? From \(-\infty\) upward OR from \(+\infty\) downward?

  • \(+\infty\) downward.


e.

There are two other mathematically equivalent ways of writing the null hypothesis here. What are they? Your answer should take the form of “\(H_0:\)________”.

  • \(H_0: \mu_{_\text{200}} - \mu_{_\text{4000}} > 0\)

  • \(H_0: \mu_{_\text{200}} > \mu_{_\text{4000}}\)



Question 8

Test \(H_0: \mu_{_\text{4000}} - \mu_{_\text{200}} < 0\) or an equivalent version of it. Report the p-value and 95% confidence interval, and state whether you reject the null hypothesis. Use of t.test() is not permitted.

# P-value
p <- pt(t, df = df, lower.tail = FALSE)
p
## [1] 0.999559
# Critical t
alpha = 0.05
t_crit <- abs(qt(alpha, df = df))

# 95% CI
low_ci <- m_diff - t_crit * se
top_ci <- m_diff + Inf * se

paste0("95% CI = [", round(low_ci, 4), ", ", top_ci, ")")
## [1] "95% CI = [-6.1034, Inf)"

Since p > 0.05 and/or 0 is contained in the confidence interval, we FAIL to reject the null hypothesis. i.e., we can’t reject the claim that the 4000 B.C.E skulls are smaller on average.

  • Note: if you subtracted the means in the opposite direction (e.g. \(\mu_{_\text{200}} - \mu_{_\text{4000}}\)) then your null hypothesis becomes \(H_0: \mu_{_\text{200}} - \mu_{_\text{4000}} > 0\). Stated this way, the critical region is in the left tail and the p-value needs to be calculated from left to right. The confidence interval would also flip (Inf, 6.1034].

Question 10

Suppose that the summary stats of your groundbreaking research are . . .

\(\bar{x}_1 = 15\)

\(\bar{x}_2 = 12\)

\(s^2_1 = 8\)

\(s^2_2 = 24\)

\(n_1 = 20\)

\(n_2 = 10\)

Verify that \(s^2_p = 13.14\), \(T = 2.14\) when rounded to two decimals, and that a classic T-test rejects the null hypothesis of equal means with \(\alpha = 0.05\). Compute a confidence interval for this hypothesis test.

m1 <- 15
m2 <- 12
var1 <- 8
var2 <- 24
n1 <- 20
n2 <- 10
alpha <- 0.05

# CALCULATIONS

# Pooled Variance
var_pool <- ((n1 - 1) * var1 + (n2 - 1) * var2) / (n1 + n2 - 2)

# Standard Error (of the Difference between groups)
se_diff <- sqrt((var_pool / n1) + (var_pool / n2))

# Test Statistic
t_stat <- ((m1 - m2) - 0) / se_diff

# Dregrees of Freedom
df <- n1 + n2 - 2

# P-Value
p <- pt(t_stat, df = df, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2

# Critical T
t_crit <- abs(qt(alpha / 2, df = df))

# Confidence Interval
bottom <- (m1 - m2) - t_crit * se_diff
top <- (m1 - m2) + t_crit * se_diff
ci <- paste0("95% CI [", round(bottom, 3), ", ", round(top, 3), "]")
# Pooled Variance
round(var_pool, 2)
## [1] 13.14
# Test Statistic
round(t_stat, 2)
## [1] 2.14
# P-Value
round(p, 3)
## [1] 0.042
# Confidence Interval
ci
## [1] "95% CI [0.124, 5.876]"

The pooled variance and the test statistic are both correct and the classic t-test rejects the hypothesis of equal means.

Question 13

Conduct a test that is designed to solve the specific problem noted by the previous question. Do the conclusions change from what you got when you ran a classic t-test? Specify the name of the test you ran, its test statistic, degrees of freedom, p-value, and two-sided 95% confidence interval.

m1 <- 15
m2 <- 12
var1 <- 8
var2 <- 24
n1 <- 20
n2 <- 10
alpha <- 0.05

# CALCULATIONS FOR WELCH T-TEST

# Degrees of Freedom
q1 <- var1 / n1
q2 <- var2 / n2

df <- ((q1 + q2)^2) / ((q1^2) / (n1 - 1) + (q2^2) / (n2 - 1))

# Standard Error of the Difference (i.e., Test Stat denominator)
se_diff <- sqrt(q1 + q2)

# Test Statistic
t_stat <- ((m1 - m2) - 0) / se_diff

# Critical T
t_crit <- abs(qt(.025, df = df))

# P-value
p <- pt(t_stat, df = df, lower.tail = FALSE) * 2

# Confidence Interval
bottom <- (m1 - m2) - t_crit * se_diff
top <- (m1 - m2) + t_crit * se_diff
## Test statistic: 1.793
## df = 12.091
## p = 0.098
## 95% CI [-0.643, 6.643]

Using a Welch T-test, \(p > .05\) and we therefore FAIL to reject \(H_0\). Yes, the results change. Using the classic test, which assumed equal variances, we had rejected the null hypothesis.



Question 14

Responses to stress are governed, in part, by the hypothalamus. Imagine you have two groups of participants. The first shows signs of heart disease and the other does not. You want to determine whether the groups differ (in any direction) in terms of the weight of the hypothalamus.

Use the data “heartDisease.csv” to determine whether the groups differ based on a classic t-test. Use \(\alpha = .05\). Use of t.test() is not permitted.

Make sure to report:

  • the test statistic
  • degrees of freedom
  • p-value
  • Confidence Interval
  • Whether your reject or fail to reject the \(H_0\)
# Data
hearts <- read_csv("../Data/heartDisease.csv")

# Get Summary Statistic Information:
  # Note I am using the summarise() function collect the group statistics I need.
  # e.g., the means, variances, sample sizes , etc.

# There are other ways you could do this, this is just convenient to stay
  # organized and makes the code more elegant when we have nasty equations
  # like the pooled variance and standard error.

stats <- hearts |>
  group_by(disease) |>
  summarise(
    n = length(hypoWeight),
    m = mean(hypoWeight),
    v = var(hypoWeight)
  )

stats
## # A tibble: 2 × 4
##   disease     n        m        v
##   <chr>   <int>    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 No         11 12.06364 14.58455
## 2 Yes        15 15.66667 31.08381
# Pooled variance
v_p <- sum((stats$n - 1) * stats$v) / sum(stats$n - 1)

# Pooled Standard Error of the Difference
se <- sqrt(sum(v_p / stats$n))

# Test Statistic
mu_diff <- 0
t <- ((stats$m[1] - stats$m[2]) - mu_diff) / se

# Degrees of Freedom
df <- sum(stats$n) - 2

# p-value
p <- pt(t, df = df) * 2

# 95% Confidence Interval
alpha <- 0.05
t_crit <- qt(alpha / 2, df = df, lower.tail = FALSE)

lower <- (stats$m[1] - stats$m[2]) - t_crit * se
upper <- (stats$m[1] - stats$m[2]) + t_crit * se
## Test statistic: -1.845
## df = 24
## p = 0.077
## 95% CI [-7.634, 0.428]

Since \(p > .05\) we FAIL to reject. There is no significant difference in hypothalamus weight between individuals with and without heart disease.

Note: By having the basic values stored in a data frame, I was able to utilize R’s ability to work with vectors. This allowed me to write code more efficiently. For instance, many people would have written pooled variance something like this:

  • v_p <- ((stats$n[1] - 1) * stats$v[1] + (stats$n[2] - 1) * stats$v[2]) / (stats$n[1] + stats$n[2] - 2)

That is long and gross. We can simplify with the sum() function:

  • v_p <- sum((stats$n - 1) * stats$v) / sum(stats$n - 1)

stats <- hearts |>

Question 18

Repeat question 14 using 20% Trimmed Means. Do you get a different conclusion? Use of yuen() is not permitted.

library(WRS2)

# Get Summary Statistic Information:
# This process is simplified greatly using the summarise() function
stats <- hearts |>
  group_by(disease) |>
  summarise(
    n = length(hypoWeight),
    G = .2,
    m = mean(hypoWeight, tr = G),
    v = winvar(hypoWeight, tr = G),
    h = n - 2 * floor(G * n),
    d = ((n - 1) * v) / (h * (h - 1))
  )

stats

Question 23

Using \(\alpha = 0.05\), assume the data come from a normally distributed population and test the hypothesis that sexual ads are remembered better than the nonsexual ads. i.e., \(H_0: \mu_{\text{sexy}} - \mu_{\text{notSexy}} > 0\). Use of t.test() is not permitted.

Make sure to report:

  • the test statistic
  • the degrees of freedom
  • p-value
  • Confidence Interval
  • Whether you reject or fail to reject \(H_0\)
#Calculate Difference Scores
diff_scores <- ad_data$AdRecall[ad_data$Image == "Sexy"] -
  ad_data$AdRecall[ad_data$Image == "NotSexy"]

#Summary Stats
N <- length(diff_scores)
m <- mean(diff_scores)
mu <- 0
se <- sd(diff_scores)/sqrt(N)

#Test Statistic
t <- (m - mu)/se

# Degrees of Freedom
df <- N - 1

# p-val
#H0: sexy > nonSexy 
# i.e., sexy - nonSexy > 0
p <- pt(t, df = df)

# Confidence interval
alpha <- 0.05
t_crit <- abs(qt(alpha, df = df))

low_ci <- m - Inf * se
top_ci <- m + t_crit * se
## T = 0.859
## df = 38
## p = 0.802
## [1] "95% CI = (-Inf, 0.6836]"

We FAIL to reject the null hypothesis that \(H_0: \mu_{\text{sexy}} - \mu_{\text{notSexy}} > 0\).



Question 24

Calculate an appropriate effect size for question 23. What is this effect size telling us? Use of cohen.d() is not permitted.

# Correlation
R <- cor(
  ad_data$AdRecall[ad_data$Image == "Sexy"],
  ad_data$AdRecall[ad_data$Image == "NotSexy"]
) # Note that the data needs to be in a logical order for this to give the correct result.

s_rm <- sd(diff_scores) / sqrt(2*(1 - R))

d <- mean(diff_scores) / s_rm

# Check number of pairs
length(ad_data$AdRecall[ad_data$Image == "Sexy"])
## [1] 39
#Since there are less than 50 pairs, we will use Hedge's g.
g <- d * (1 - (3 / (4*(df)-1)))
g
## [1] 0.1314418

The difference in recall between the two types of ads is small, amounting to approximately 0.131 standard deviations.

Question 26

Plot a bar graph showing the means of both groups and their difference. Give each bar an errorbar that corresponds to a two-sided 95% confidence interval around the mean.

#Add difference scores to the dataframe
diff_data <- data.frame(
  Subject = 1:39,
  AdRecall = diff_scores,
  Image = c(rep("Difference", 39))
)

ad_data_diff <- rbind(ad_data, diff_data)
# Obtain values for plot
plot_data <- ad_data_diff %>%
  group_by(Image) %>%
  summarise(
    n = length(AdRecall),
    m = mean(AdRecall),
    se = sd(AdRecall) / sqrt(n),
    df = n - 1,
    alpha = 0.05,
    t_crit = abs(qt(alpha / 2, df)),
    moe = se * t_crit,
    lower = m - t_crit,
    upper = m + t_crit
  )
# Factoring data to put bars in a sensible order
plot_data$Image <- factor(plot_data$Image,
  levels = c("Sexy", "NotSexy", "Difference")
)
# For reference, here are the plotting values

Question 27

Use a Q-Q plot to assess the normality of the sexSells.csv data. Why do you think the plot looks so strange? (You won’t loose marks if your are incorrect).

ggplot(mapping = aes(sample = diff_scores)) +
  stat_qq(size = 3) +
  stat_qq_line() +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 20))

It looks strange because there are numerous repetitions of the same value. If you examine the difference scores you will find five -2’s, seven -1’s, nine 0’s and so on. It’s worth considering how you might prevent this issue when designing your own studies.



Question 28

Repeat question 23 using 20% trimmed means.

  • Hint: We never covered a trimmed version of the paired t-test in class; however, we did cover a trimmed version of a one-sample t-test.
library(WRS2)

N <- length(diff_scores)
mu <- 0
G <- 0.2
m <- mean(diff_scores, tr = G)
var <- winvar(diff_scores, tr = G)
s <- sqrt(var)
se <- s / ((1 - 2 * G) * sqrt(N))

# Degrees of Freedom
h <- N - 2 * floor(G * N)
df <- h - 1

# Test Statistic
t <- (m - mu) / se

# p-val
# H0: sexy > nonSexy
# i.e., sexy - nonSexy > 0
p <- pt(t, df = df)

# Confidence interval
alpha <- 0.05
t_crit <- abs(qt(alpha, df = df))

low_ci <- m - Inf * se
top_ci <- m + t_crit * se
## T = 0.651
## df = 24
## p = 0.739
## [1] "95% CI = (-Inf, 0.7254]"

We fail to reject the null hypothesis that \(H_0: Sexy - NotSexy > 0\).
